    slug: "mukhtasir-zaadul-maaad-arabic",
    description: `Mukhtasir Zaad ul Ma'ad is an abridged Arabic-language edition of the renowned work "Zaad al-Ma'ad fi Hadyi Khayr al-Ibad" (Provisions for the Hereafter in the Guidance of the Best of Servants) by the great Islamic scholar Imam Ibn al-Qayyim al-Jawziyyah, one of the most celebrated students of Shaykh al-Islam Ibn Taymiyyah. The original work is a comprehensive encyclopedia of the life and practices of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), covering every aspect of his daily routine, worship, social interactions, personal habits, and spiritual disciplines in meticulous detail, all drawn exclusively from authentic sources. This mukhtasir condenses the multi-volume original into a single manageable volume while preserving the essential content, the most important narrations, and the key scholarly observations that have made Zaad al-Ma'ad one of the most frequently referenced works on the Prophetic biography (seerah) and the Prophet's guidance (hadiyyah). The book is organised chronologically and thematically, beginning with the Prophet's guidance regarding the remembrance of Allah, supplication, and the morning and evening adhkar, then proceeding through his guidance on purification, the prayer, the Friday congregation, the funeral prayer, fasting, charity, pilgrimage, and all other acts of worship. Extensive sections cover the Prophet's guidance on food and drink, clothing and adornment, sleeping and waking, travelling, sickness and health, marriage and family life, treatment of servants, interaction with neighbours, dealing with the poor and needy, and his conduct in both peace and warfare. The book also covers the Prophet's character traits, his emotional expressions, his sense of humour, his anger, his grief, and his expressions of love and compassion, presenting a complete and balanced picture of the man whom Allah described as an "excellent example" for all believers. The abridgement maintains the original author's method of citing the hadith sources for every practice he describes, allowing readers to verify the authenticity of each narration independently. The Arabic text is presented in a clear format with full vowel marks where necessary for proper understanding, and the scholarly commentary that accompanies each narration provides context and explains the significance and practical application of the Prophetic practice being described. This abridged Arabic edition is particularly valuable for students of Islamic knowledge who wish to study the original text in Arabic without committing to the full multi-volume set, and for Arabic-speaking readers who want a comprehensive yet manageable reference on the complete guidance of Prophet Muhammad.`,
